<br>
*shrug*<br>
You're right.  Mistakes will always be made.  Some guilty people go free.  Some not-guilty people get jailed.  If you're suggesting that &quot;it's okay to jail him for ten years, but oh no don't castrate him because what if we're wrong?&quot;  That's just plain wishy-washy and foolish.  If you think you may be wrong, set him free.  Does your own justice system not dictate that if you think you are wrong (if there is even a shadow of a doubt), you must find him innocent?<br>
<br>
What would you suggest?  Let him appeal a few times and then castrate him?  Okay, I'm fine with that.  But to just let him go in ten or fifteen years so he can re-offend is ignorant and not cost-effective on the judiciary system.<br>
<br>
If you're going to find them guilty, treat them like they're guilty.<br>
<br>
